<misra_rule>
The target MISRA C 2023 Rule 2.1 is: A project shall not contain unreachable code.

</misra_rule>
<instruction>
Other agents will judge whether the code follows the MISRA C 2023 guidelines.
They will investigate the code fragments you give.
Your job is to find code fragments in the code that should be investigated to check whether the code follows the MISRA C rule.
</instruction>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- suspicious_frags: The list of suspicious code fragments in the code.
It should contain only the code fragments exists in the code. If you do not find any suspicious code fragments, return an empty list for suspicious_frags
- explanation: The explanation of why other code fragments should NOT be investigated.
It is very important to not miss any suspicious code fragments, so please give a sufficient explanation why other code fragments should not be investigated.
DO NOT give any explanation for the selected suspicious code fragments.
</response format>
<target_code>
Here is the code of mhd_tool_get_sys_cpu_count_sysconf_:
```c
static int
mhd_tool_get_sys_cpu_count_sysconf_ (void)
{
  int ret = -1;
#if defined(HAVE_SYSCONF) && \
  (defined(HAS_DECL__SC_NPROCESSORS_ONLN) || defined(HAS_DECL__SC_NPROC_ONLN))
  long value = -1;
#ifdef HAS_DECL__SC_NPROCESSORS_ONLN
  if (0 >= value)
    value = sysconf (_SC_NPROCESSORS_ONLN);
#endif /* HAS_DECL__SC_NPROCESSORS_ONLN */
#ifdef HAS_DECL__SC_NPROC_ONLN
  if (0 >= value)
    value = sysconf (_SC_NPROC_ONLN);
#endif /* HAS_DECL__SC_NPROC_ONLN */
  if (0 >= value)
    return -1;
  ret = (int) value;
  if ((long) ret != value)
    return -1; /* Overflow */
#endif /* HAVE_SYSCONF &&
          (HAS_DECL__SC_NPROCESSORS_ONLN || HAS_DECL__SC_NPROC_ONLN) */
  return ret;
}
```
</target_code>
<additional code>Here are the definitions of symbols that are related to the target function mhd_tool_get_sys_cpu_count_sysconf_:
#define HAVE_SYSCONF 1
...
#define HAS_DECL__SC_NPROCESSORS_ONLN 1
</additional code>
Please find suspicious code fragments in the code and report them. Other agents can not investigate other fragments that you do not report, so it is very important to find all suspicious fragments without missing any. Report the suspicious fragments AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE.
explanation: Other code fragments do not need investigation for reachability: the enclosing #if that enables the sysconf-based implementation is true given the provided defines, so that part of the function is present in the build. The initialization of `value` and the subsequent check that returns -1 if `value` remains non-positive are reachable at runtime (they handle sysconf returning <= 0). The assignment to `ret` and the overflow check comparing `(long) ret != value` are reachable if sysconf returns a positive value possibly outside int range, so they are necessary runtime checks. The final `return ret;` is reachable (it returns the default -1 when runtime queries fail). Therefore these remaining fragments do not present obvious unreachable-code issues under the supplied configuration.
